I’ve been meaning to post about this for awhile. I’ve shared it in stories and always get a ton of DMs on how to cope when climbing. This is just my experience, I know other people struggle with this in slightly different ways, but these are things I’ve found to be the most helpful in climbing thru it.
This is Raynaud’s Syndrome. It’s a hypersensitivity to decreasing temperatures. I struggle with it in grocery stores, cold water, air conditioning, and especially, alpine climbing environments. Triggering it is less about ambient coldness and more related to a drop in temp on exposed skin. For example: breaking a sweat while hiking in, then stopping to rack up in a cool breeze. In that scenario the air temp could be 55-60 degrees F but a cool breeze will still trigger a Raynaud’s attack. 
When triggered the capillary beds shut down and ALL the blood drains from my fingers. Touching things feels like 1000 needles and I have very little control over using my fingers. The cycle runs from total white shut down to a grey low oxygen state when the capillaries are refilling (pic 4 and 5). The whole process usually takes about 45 min-1 hour to get back to normal. 
Things I learned about dealing with this: 
✏️ I can’t prevent it, if I’m in a high risk situation it’s better to LET IT HAPPEN on the ground than risk it happening on the wall. 
✏️ I can speed up the process by windmilling my arms to use centrifugal force to push blood back into my fingers. This can cut recovery down to 30ish minutes.
✏️ 99% of the time it will only happen once per circumstance. After I recover the process doesn’t repeat in that environment that day. 
✏️ I cannot train my body out of this… don’t come at me with the ice baths. 
✏️ The more depleted I am the harder it is to recover. Maintaining hydration and calories helps me bounce back faster. 
✏️ It’s best to plan for my alpine partners to lead the first pitch. 
✏️ I don’t end my climbing day over it anymore I just make sure my partner knows what’s happening, go thru the steps to recover and then carry on. I DO NOT get back on lead until my fingers are pink again! 

#alpineclimbing #raynauds #climberproblems

After I posted about Raynaud’s a few days ago and comments started to roll in I realized I wrote that with an alpine climbing perspective in mind and I do handle it differently in different situations.
In the alpine I make no effort to prevent an attack. I actually try to get it out of the way before the climbing starts. In my experience prevention (like using hand warmers or gloves) only results in a delay. If I don’t go thru it on the ground it will only happen later at a higher belay or mid-pitch making things more complex and scary. Plus my hands don’t usually trigger multiple times in a setting, so one and done.
For cragging I do try to prevent/delay it. Usually as soon as I get to the climbs I eat something and cover my arms (sleeves with thumb loops 🙌). Keeping the wind off my skin is a huge help. So is not letting my circulation stagnate if I was hiking. I try to stay upright and move around, bouncing and jumping jacks if necessary. I also check out the rock temp. If the rocks are really cold, especially in the morning, that will do it and an attack can develop fast enough to be debilitating mid-pitch. Which on bolts is not usually a huge deal but it can be on a trad route. The first time this happened climbing I actually got stuck in a tree because I couldn’t place gear or down climb. 🫣
If it triggers I just go thru the same process of mechanically forcing blood back into my fingers. Windmilling, a little cardio, dance party, ect. As far as I can tell, for me, it’s much more about circulation than actual temp. I don’t usually use hand warmers anymore because I can’t maintain contact with them all the time and the warmers don’t help to bring me out of it, I could be in 3 layers of down jacket but if I’m not stimulating circulation my fingers will stay white longer.
I’ve never taken prescription meds for it, and maybe that’s something to look into but I also use Adderall to manage ADHD so that might be a contraindication… continued in comments.

He did great btw. 👏👏👏
Be prepared if you climb Prevertical on the Diamond, the wide pitch is way longer than 80ft, and if your hands are 1s you’ll definitely have to offwidth. 👊🫷

Some climbers were talking about this a few days ago at the crag and I wanted to put my scientific 2 cents out there… 

ADHD symptoms are caused by a deficiency in norepinephrine and its precursor dopamine. Norephinephrine is crucial to the regulation of attention, cognitive function, and stress reactions while dopamine is responsible for allowing you to feel pleasure, satisfaction and motivation.

Climbing, with its tangible consequences and immediacy, creates a stress response that increases these neurotransmitters. For a neurotypical person this can feel like anxiety and over stimulation, but for a neurodivergent climber this actually puts us closer to ‘normal’ levels. We can think clearer, have more sustained motivation and are at the same time still calm enough to solve problems because our brains are in optimal stimulation. 

ADHD climbers are the people you want around in a crisis, our brains are literally wired for high pressure situations. 

Cover photo by @yeahapril from Wild Iris. 💜

Been spending a lot of time at crack house this trip and it honestly feels like an oasis from the hellscape this year has been. I don’t mind the long slightly 4x4 drive, the views are worth it and I can park right next to it with my injured pup who happily watches rodents while I work on the endurance to send this thing. 

Unrelated: This place (IG) has felt hard to exist in for a long time. Way longer than I wanted it to. I’ve been totally burnt out on trying to feel interesting, don’t have many wins to share, am frequently consumed by my job and don’t have time to spend editing the content this platform demands. 

Social media for me has been a moneyless extra job that I couldn’t take breaks from. Inconsistency is punished by the algorithm and the rules change so fast if you don’t participate you can’t keep up. That being said for whatever reasons I’m still here, muddling thru, sharing stuff when I can and playing with new bullshit like AI editing. Please enjoy slide 3 where AI turned Eldo into a baby cow. 😂

So I took the fall you’re not supposed to take at Crackhouse… half upside down from the last move on the top. Thankfully a crew of spotters kept my head off the ground and just my elbow managed to thread the needle and find a rock. (This is a tame pic of how gross it actually got.) Fortunately, it only needed three stitches and a tetanus shot, but a lesson was learned about padding the sloping boulder pit on the left. 

I guess that’s a wrap for now, I need to not use my left arm much for a few days and it’s been a messy month in the desert. Zero goals were accomplished and work burnout peaked, but two dog surgeries were completed and we all survived. 👏 #couldbeworse #crashpadawareness

Climbing isn’t only what I do for fun, it’s actually a part of my job too. I’ve been working on testing the new Crack Gloves PRO over the past couple of months and there’s been several rounds of tweaking and evaluation, listening to feedback from users and talking to the design team. I’ve never gotten this close to product development before and it’s pretty fascinating. 

I think as a consumer it’s easy to think why don’t they just make this perfect??? But ‘perfect’ changes in every context and frequently there are mechanical or material limitations that can’t bee see from a user experience. Balancing the give and take of changing one thing to improve another and maintaining satisfaction across different user groups is pretty much a never ending challenge. 

It’s been fun and educational to get to participate in the puzzle of getting a new product to final production. While the factories in Czech are hard at work on production I’m looking forward to seeing the climbing community get their hands on these to put them thru their paces and get even more feedback on the final result.

Sometimes I get all questy on a formation I’ve looked at for awhile and it’s super fun. Other times… well, this was one of those other times. 😅 
Spent a little time exploring Overlook Pinnacle and got reminded that the Lemmon can be pretty weird. This arete is supposed to climb as a trad variation but didn’t appear to have placements or bolts above the roof. Maybe they’re blind, maybe they’re not there, maybe the terrain is so easy you just run it out. Either way I wasn’t in the mood to try and find out. So I bailed from some nuts and climbed a bolted 11 instead. 🤷🏻‍♀️🍋

We spent the last day of the year checking out Obscure Rock, almost the last crag if you hike all the way out Windy Point (which is really only 10 minutes from the car 😁). I’ve never walked out there but the routes were fun and the hang was outstanding. 

Note: If you check it out some of the anchors prob need replacing… they’re also prob good enough, but use your judgement and back them up if you’re not confident. This route was Aurora Blues and the left bolt of the anchor looked pretty ragged to me. 😬
